  "bib_entries": {
    "154098498": {
      "title": "Nominal price rigidity, money supply endogeneity and business cycle",
      "abstract": "Abstract This paper investigates the ability of nominal price rigidity to explain the co-movement of inflation with the cyclical component of output observed in the post-war U.S. data. A dynamic general equilibrium model is constructed with the introduction of monopolistic competition and nominal price rigidity in a standard real business cycle model, allowing for an endogenous money supply rule. It is then demonstrated that sticky price models can explain the observed associations between movements in inflation and output much better than flexible price models. This result depends little on whether money supply is assumed to be endogenous or not."
    },
    "154060326": {
      "title": "Generating real persistent effects of monetary shocks: How much nominal rigidity do we really need?",
      "abstract": "This paper attempts to assess whether money can generate persistent economic\" fluctuations in dynamic general equilibrium models of the business cycle. We show that a small\" nominal friction in the goods market can make the response of output to monetary shocks large\" and persistent if it is amplified by real wage rigidity in the labor market. We also argue that\" given the level of real wage rigidity that is observed in developed countries nominal stickiness might be sufficient for money to produce economic fluctuations as persistent\" as those observed in the data."
    }
  }
}